\begin_layout Title
Stochastic Differential Equations - A Primer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
stochastic process
\series default
 is a collection of random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X_{t}\left(s\right):t\in T,s\in S\right\} $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

is some index set (usually representing time) and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the common sample space of all the random variables.
 For each fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 denotes a single random variable defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 For each fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a function defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 that is called a 
\series bold
sample path
\series default
 or 
\series bold
stochastic realization
\series default
 of the process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example*
Consider a random walk on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,\pm\Delta x,\pm2\Delta x,\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be the prob.
 of going right, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 the prob.
 of going left with 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be the discrete time Markov chain for this random walk with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left\{ 0,\Delta t,2\Delta t,\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)\in\left\{ 0,\pm\Delta x,\pm2\Delta x,\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}\left(t\right)=\Pr\left(X\left(t\right)=x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider stochastic processes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ X\left(t\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 which are continuous in both time and in state.
 Time, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, goes from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is either in: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-\infty,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,M\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Definitions and Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
Markov process
\series default
 is one that satisfies the following property.
 Given any sequence of times 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}<t_{1}<\cdots<t_{n-1}<t_{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ X\left(t_{n}\right)\le y|X\left(t_{0}\right)=x_{0},X\left(t_{1}\right)=x_{1},\ldots,X\left(t_{n-1}\right)=x_{n-1}\right\} =\Pr\left\{ X\left(t_{n}\right)\le y|X\left(t_{n-1}\right)=x_{n-1}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 the future state only depends on the current state 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t_{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and not any of the past history.
 This property is known as the 
\series bold
Markov property
\series default
 (memorylessness).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(y,s;x,t\right)=\Pr\left\{ X\left(s\right)=y|X\left(t\right)=x\right\} $
\end_inset

, the transition probability density function (pdf).
 The transition pdf is 
\series bold
homogeneous
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(y,s+\Delta t;x,t+\Delta t\right)=p\left(y,s;x,t\right)
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 the transition probability only depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $s-t$
\end_inset

, the difference in the time points.
 In this case, we might also write 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(y,x,s-t\right)=p\left(y,s;x,t\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition pdf satisfies an important identity known as the 
\series bold
Chapman-Kolmogorov equations
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(y,s;x,t\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}p\left(y,s;z,u\right)p\left(z,u;x,t\right)dz
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $t<u<s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dynamics of these processes depend on the initial density of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Frequently, the initial density is assumed to be concentrated at a point
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

, so that the pdf of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t_{0}\right)=\delta\left(x-x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, the Diract delta function at 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we might write 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x,t;x_{0},t_{0}\right)=p\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(x,t\right)=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}p\left(x,t;z,u\right)p\left(z,u\right)dz
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}<u<t$
\end_inset

.
 Don't let the notation confuse you.
 To calculate a probability associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 we need to integrate
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left(X\left(t\right)\in\left[a,b\right]\right)=\int_{a}^{b}p\left(x,t\right)dx
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Random Walks and Brownian Motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a random walk on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,\pm\Delta x,\pm2\Delta x,\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be the prob.
 of going right, 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 the prob.
 of going left with 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q=1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be the discrete time Markov chain for this random walk with 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left\{ 0,\Delta t,2\Delta t,\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)\in\left\{ 0,\pm\Delta x,\pm2\Delta x,\ldots\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x}\left(t\right)=\Pr\left(X\left(t\right)=x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,t\right)=p_{x}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(x,t+\Delta t\right)=pu\left(x-\Delta x,t\right)+qu\left(x+\Delta x,t\right)
\]

\end_inset

Now we will let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t\to0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Expand the RHS of the equation about using Taylor's formula about the point
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u\left(x,t+\Delta t\right) & =p\left[u\left(x,t\right)+\frac{\partial u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x}\left(-\Delta x\right)+\frac{\partial^{2}u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x^{2}}\frac{\left(-\Delta x\right)^{2}}{2}+O\left(\left(\Delta x\right)^{3}\right)\right]+\ldots\\
 & +q\left[u\left(x,t\right)+\frac{\partial u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x}\left(\Delta x\right)+\frac{\partial^{2}u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x^{2}}\frac{\left(\Delta x\right)^{2}}{2}+O\left(\left(\Delta x\right)^{3}\right)\right]\\
 & =u\left(x,t\right)+\left(q-p\right)\frac{\partial u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x}\left(\Delta x\right)+\frac{\partial^{2}u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x^{2}}\frac{\left(\Delta x\right)^{2}}{2}+O\left(\left(\Delta x\right)^{3}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Form a difference quotient wrt 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{u\left(x,t+\Delta t\right)-u\left(x,t\right)}{\Delta t}=\left(q-p\right)\frac{\partial u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x}\left(\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x^{2}}\frac{\left(\Delta x\right)^{2}}{\Delta t}+O\left(\frac{\left(\Delta x\right)^{3}}{\Delta t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

We need the following assumptions (we'll try to justify them later)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lim_{\Delta t,\Delta x\to0}\left(p-q\right)\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t} & =c,\\
\lim_{\Delta t,\Delta x\to0}\frac{\left(\Delta x\right)^{2}}{\Delta t} & =D,\\
\lim_{\Delta t,\Delta x\to0}\frac{\left(\Delta x\right)^{3}}{\Delta t} & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now, letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x,\Delta t\to0$
\end_inset

 above, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial t}=-c\frac{\partial u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x}+\frac{D}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u\left(x,t\right)}{\partial x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

This is known as the diffusion equation with drift, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
diffusion coefficient
\series default
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
drift coefficient
\series default
.
 It is also known as the forward Kolmogorov differential equation corresponding
 to the stochastic process we described above.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $p=q=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0$
\end_inset

 and the movement is unbiased or symmetric.
 This stochastic process is then known as 
\series bold
Brownian motion
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}=\frac{D}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that the initial density is 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(x,0\right)=\delta\left(x-x_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, the solution to the initial value problem above is the normal density
 function with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}+ct$
\end_inset

 and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $Dt$
\end_inset

 ,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(x,t\right)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi Dt}}\exp\left(-\frac{\left(x-x_{0}-ct\right)^{2}}{2Dt}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

